function rotateGrid(grid, k) {
    function rotateLayer(layer, k) {
        const m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
        const top = layer, bottom = m - 1 - layer;
        const left = layer, right = n - 1 - layer;
        const data_in_layer = (right - left + 1) * 2 + (bottom - top - 1) * 2;
        k %= data_in_layer;
        while (k-- > 0) {
            const temp = grid[top][left];
            for (let j = left; j < right; j++) grid[top][j] = grid[top][j + 1];
            for (let i = top; i < bottom; i++) grid[i][right] = grid[i + 1][right];
            for (let j = right; j > left; j--) grid[bottom][j] = grid[bottom][j - 1];
            for (let i = bottom; i > top; i--) grid[i][left] = grid[i - 1][left];
            grid[top + 1][left] = temp;
        }
    }

    const m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
    const layers = Math.min(m, n) / 2;
    for (let layer = 0; layer < layers; layer++) {
        rotateLayer(layer, k);
    }
    return grid;
}
```

    The algorithm works as follows:
1. Calculate the number of layers in the matrix based on its dimensions, since m and n are both even integers, this number will always be an integer.
2. For each layer, create a helper function `rotateLayer` to rotate the layer k times counter-clockwise. Calculate data_in_layer which is the number of cells belonging to that layer. 
3. Perform k % data_in_layer rotations to avoid unnecessary complete rotations. 
4. Each rotation is done as follows: save the top-left corner value, move the top row cells to the left, move the right column cells up, move the bottom row cells to the right, move the left column cells down, save the stored top-left corner value to top row's second cell. 

The algorithm performs the rotations for each layer, and returns the rotated grid.

